AB  - This study assessed the executive functioning and behavioral self-regulation of 7-11 year-old adopted children via parent interview, behavior rating forms, and computerized neuropsychological testing. It was predicted that early relationship adversity would be associated with deficits in neuropsychological functioning, such that children who experienced instability and maltreatment would demonstrate below average performance on tasks of executive functioning. Results indicated that adopted children performed more poorly than the standardization sample on computerized tasks of executive function. Although early relationship adversity was not a significant predictor of performance on computerized tasks of executive function, it was a significant predictor of adopted children's behavioral self-regulation problems as assessed by parent behavior rating instruments. Specifically, early relationship adversity was associated with poor inhibitory control, inattention, aggression, rule-breaking behaviors, and working memory difficulties. Children's executive functioning problems were also associated with high levels of parenting stress and low levels of parental acceptance. Findings provide information about aspects of early care that can place children at risk for developing executive functioning and self-regulatory deficits. This study may have implications for interventions and policy regarding adopted children and their caregivers. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)
