AB  - Reviews the book, A Practical Guide to Caring for Children and Teenagers with Attachment Difficulties by C. Taylor (2010). This book is a resource for practitioners that is aimed at professionals working with, and living alongside troubled children such as residential and foster carers. It has been written by an author with a wealth of practice experience in this area. The book presents a therapeutic approach that is underpinned by an understanding of how attachment relationships influence the emotional, cognitive and behavioral development of them. The approach is a behavioral one in the sense that attachment theory describes patterns of organized behavior within a relationship, and the outlined strategies for working with children are focused on managing their behavior. The book gives a rich and detailed account of how attachment difficulties in early life impact on future development and offers practical guidance on how to work with children in a way that mitigates these past difficulties and helps them recover. The book is divided into eight chapters. The first chapter is called 'Patterns of Attachment' and outlines an understanding of attachment that is based around the theory of John Bowlby and the experimental research of Mary Ainsworth. The remaining seven chapters take different aspects of a therapeutic mode based around working with a child who has a negative Internal Working Model (IWM) to develop a positive one, by creating an environment in which the child can develop secure attachments. This book explores the impact of attachment difficulties on the behavior of young people and offers a therapeutic framework and approach to care that attempts to address this behavior. It offers a valuable resource to practitioners who work directly with young people, providing them with a strategy and practical tools to manage difficult behavior in a way that supports young people and ensures their recovery. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights rese