AB  - This study was designed to add to our knowledge about the impact of intensive case management (ICM) on the level of functioning of severely emotionally disturbed (SED) adolescents in out-of-home care. Three hypotheses were tested in this research: SED adolescents receiving ICM, after six months of intervention, would (1) demonstrate a higher level of social competence and a greater decrease in behavioral/emotional problems, (2) a higher level of school functioning, and (3) a higher level of residential functioning than SED adolescents receiving foster care case management (FCCM). The participants in the study were 71 adolescents in the custody of the South Carolina Department of Social Services who, (1) were in out-of-home placement and (2) met the CASSP criteria for SED. The study used a field based, experimental design with simple random assignment to two treatment groups--intensive case management (ICM) and foster care case management (FCCM). ICM was clearly defined and operationalized and multiple measures of outcomes were used at both the system and interpersonal level. The Youth Self-Report was used to measure the adolescents' levels of social competence and behavioral/emotional problems. Over the six months of the intervention, data were collected on the factors associated with the population, case managers, the treatment intervention, and the interrelationship among these factors. Analysis revealed that the majority of the adolescents were diagnosed with character disorder or attention deficit disorder, had spent extensive time in foster care, and were placed in residential treatment facilities. The primary case management activity was monitoring, followed by assessment and planning. The findings provided evidence that ICM adolescents achieved a higher level of social functioning and moved to less restrictive residential placements than those adolescents receiving FCCM. Implications for social work practice, research, and education are discussed. (Psyc