AB  - Due to recent advances in medical technology, children who were once relegated to a life of institutionalization can now be cared for in the home. Children with medical needs are overrepresented in the general foster care population; however, many children with chronic physical conditions require a specialized home environment that is equipped to manage their complex needs. While most outcome evaluations of treatment foster care programs have focused on placement permanency, safety, or psychological adjustment as primary outcome measures, other important variables, such as developmental functioning, have gone largely neglected. Given that children with complex medical conditions are at risk for compromised developmental adjustment, it is important to understand child, parent, and family factors that facilitate more positive adjustment. The present study used data that were collected from children and foster parents who were enrolled in a treatment foster care program in a large Midwestern metropolitan area, Measures used in this study included the Denver Developmental Screening Test - II, the Questionnaire on Resources and Stress - Friedrich Edition, the Multidimensional Scale of Perceived Social Support, and the Mentor Interview, developed for this research, As a group, the children showed improved developmental functioning over the six-month period. The children who were functioning closer to their age at initial placement exhibited greater developmental progress than the other children in the sample. Similarly, children with less severe medical conditions showed more developmental progress over the study period when compared to children with more severe medical conditions. Foster parents' social support was not found to predict developmental gain, nor was it found to moderate the relationship between stress and developmental gain. Post-hoc analysis revealed that foster parents' stress did significantly predict child developmental gain, with lower stress scores being associated with greater developmental gain. These findings are inconclusive, given the dearth of research in this area, along with several methodological limitations. Nevertheless, they provide an encouraging indication that treatment foster care is a viable intervention model that can be enhanced by attention to various child and parent factors.
