AB  - One of the more basic ways to improve a bond between two individuals who wish to enhance their relationship is to increase physical connections, or closeness. Linked-In activities allow clients (typically parents and children) to be closer to one another without that appearing to be the main focus of therapy. Initially, the first time this activity is attempted, there may not seem to be much of an effect in increasing proximity, but over time, repeated use of this activity can foster attachment and a closer, more trusting relationship. The focus of this activity is for each client (parent or child) to use only one hand to work together to accomplish a task, which is selected either by the therapist or by the clients. Focusing on the task diverts attention from the physical proximity, lessens resistance, and demonstrates to clients that they can rely on one another and enjoy themselves as they accomplish a task. Initial success can be built upon by increasingly difficult Linked-In activities as therapy progresses. Linked-In is especially useful for clients who would like to strengthen their relationship and increase physical proximity. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)
