AB  - Limited success in describing and measuring potential powerful variables related to child, family, and service variables that affect outcome in therapeutic foster care has restricted the ability to develop an effective system of care for children. This study tested and used newly developed/modified scales and questionnaires measuring the impact of foster family suitability for fostering, quality of the milieu in the foster home, and program supports on change in the child's functioning (Global Assessment of Functioning Scale admission scores minus post-placement scores). Fifty-five foster parents parenting seventy-seven foster children and twelve social workers participated. Subjects were drawn from therapeutic foster care programs within two local non-profit agencies. Case records provided children's admission age, gender, previous placements, and admission functioning. A multivariate correlational design was used. Findings indicate social workers' assessment of quality conditions in foster homes predict change in child functioning in terms of attachment and caretaking, affection and acceptance. Child characteristics had no significant relationship with change in child functioning. Foster parents' suitability for fostering was not correlated with change in child functioning post-placement, but the regression analyses of the social workers' assessment of quality conditions in a foster home and the Foster Parent Assessment Scale relating to health, interpersonal relationships, adaptability, and team member accounted for the largest variance in the dependent variable. Foster fathers' overall satisfaction with program support was tested to be a critical factor related to change in child functioning. Although findings are targeted to therapeutic foster homes served by two agencies, all scales demonstrated appropriate levels of reliability and discriminate ability with this population. These scales are recommended to select foster parents and measure ability to create an effective treatment milieu. Use of the GAF to determine changes in child functioning is a reliable outcome strategy. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
