AB  - Parents who have adopted children from state's custody are charged with parenting children who have experienced different aspects of trauma and loss. This trauma and loss often negatively impacts child behavior, which may leave parents confused, frustrated, and possibly at risk for adoption disruption or dissolution. This study surveyed 315 primary parents of children who were adopted from state's custody to predict parenting stress by assessing their adult attachment style, their perception of their partner's attachment style, and their reports of family functioning. Primary parents also answered demographic questions inspired by Rosenthal's (1993) study of seven predictive factors that predict adoption disruption. The Experiences in Close Relationships--Revised (R. Fraley, Waller, & Brennan, 2000) assessed adult attachment, while family functioning was measured using the Family Adaptability and Cohesion Evaluation Scale IV (D. Olson, 2008). The Parental Stress Scale (Berry & Jones, 1995) accounted for the parenting stress of the oldest adoptive child. Using multiple regression, this study found higher levels of attachment-related anxiety and avoidance predicted parenting stress. Primary parents who perceived their partners to have higher levels of attachment-related anxiety and avoidance also predicted parenting stress. Finally, families who reported higher levels of family cohesion and flexibility significantly predicted less parenting stress. Results of this study indicate the importance of these assessments for agencies that place children, the need for parental support from friends, utilization of attachment and system-based interventions with clinicians working with adoptive families. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2018 APA, all rights reserved)
