AB  - For mothers of twins, the physical, psychological, and social changes that occur in the first year of motherhood are greatly intensified, often resulting in increased stress, feelings of inadequacy, and social isolation. This study used both quantitative and qualitative methods to evaluate the effects of a psychosocial support group intervention on mothers' of twins parenting stress and parenting sense of competency. Mothers with twins under 12 months of age self-selected participation in either a treatment group (N = 6) or comparison group (N = 6) and completed the Parenting Stress Inventory (PSI) and the Parenting Sense of Competence Scale (PSOC) as pretest and posttest measurements. Treatment group mothers participated in a six-session, weekly psychosocial support group and were then interviewed in order to assess their perceptions of the group experience. Analysis of variance (ANOVA) revealed a significantly greater decrease in level of parenting stress and increase in parenting sense of competence for the treatment group mothers than for comparison group mothers. The data gathered from the qualitative interviews revealed that treatment group mothers perceived the psychosocial support group to be helpful in lowering their levels of parenting stress and increasing their parenting sense of competence through offering psychological and emotional support, providing information concerning practical issues related to parenting twins, and fostering the development of a relevant network of social support. This study provides quantitative evidence of the benefits of participation in a psychosocial support group for mothers of twins, as well qualitative data concerning participants' perceptions of the components that contribute to a successful group intervention. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
