AB  - The purpose of this dissertation project is to create a preventive parenting program for parents of toddlers. This program would educate parents on common developmental and behavioral issues of toddlers and incorporate aspects of Parent-Child Interaction Therapy (PCIT) to provide parents with sound interventions to toddler specific behavioral problems. The Parent-Toddler Relationship Enrichment Program aims to increase parental competence, reduce parental stress, and strengthen the parent-toddler relationship. The author chose to model part of the Parent-Toddler Relationship Enrichment Program after PCIT, because PCIT is a statistically validated intervention for toddler behavioral disorders, focuses on the parent as the main mediator of child behavior, has proven to have long lasting success over a variety of parent-child relationship problems, and its behaviorally oriented techniques are easily grasped and retained by most parents. The key, however, is to take this clinically based treatment and incorporate some of its theories and techniques in a preventive parenting program in order to reach a wider population before the parent-child relationship becomes dysfunctional. PCIT is an empirically validated parent focused treatment model designed for children ages two to seven with disruptive behavior disorders. The model of treatment is based on two phases: the relationship building phase, and the discipline phase. The relationship building phase is focused on enhancing the parent-child relationship by teaching parent specific techniques which foster a nurturing and secure bond with the child. The discipline phase focuses on teaching parents to effectively set limits and boundaries to reduce their child's negative behaviors. PCIT is conducted in a clinic setting in an average of fifteen to twenty sessions. The Parent-Toddler Relationship Enrichment Program is a unique preventive parenting program because it combines education of toddler development with principles and techniques of PCIT in a parenting program designed to reach a larger, non-clinic population before the parent-child relationship becomes problematic. The Parent-Toddler Relationship Enrichment Program will consist of three sessions held in a workshop format. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
