AB  - The present study examined the sequelae of attachment for 557 children in foster care. Children at high risk for insecure attachment and children at low risk for insecure attachment were compared on social, behavioral, and cognitive measures. It was hypothesized that social competence (communication skills and social skills) and behavioral adjustment (total number of behavior problems, internalizing behavior, and externalizing behavior) would be closely associated with attachment risk group, and gender differences would be observed in the high-risk group. Cognitive functioning was also hypothesized to be associated with attachment but to a lesser degree than either social competence or behavioral adjustment. Results of the study confirm that attachment risk group was associated with social competence and behavioral adjustment, but not with cognitive functioning. Children who were considered to be at high-risk for insecure attachment were rated as being less socially competent and demonstrating more externalizing, internalizing, and total behavior problems than children at low-risk for insecure attachment. Although these differences were statistically significant, the mean scores for both attachment risk groups were within the normal range on all measures, and therefore, the practical difference in applied settings between these groups would probably be minimal. Girls demonstrated significantly greater communication skills than boys, regardless of attachment group. A non-significant interaction was observed between attachment risk group and gender for social skills; girls in the low risk group scored substantially higher than boys in the high risk group. Gender differences were not noted on any of the three behavioral variables. Effect sizes for the findings were small; raising the question of whether being at high- or low-risk for insecure attachment has practical significance for at-risk children in foster care. Implications for interventions with children in foster care and attachment theory, limitations to the current study, and directions for future research are discussed. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
