AB  - Comments on an article by L. Murray et al. (see record [rid]2015-39446-001[/rid]). After many years of neglect the message is finally out that early childhood is critically important and has long-term effects on individual and maybe even 'national' development. The South African intervention by Murray et al. began in pregnancy and continued to 6 months of age and was aimed at improving maternal sensitivity and attachment. Attachment did improve but there was no overall benefit on the children’s mental development. The authors suggest that improving maternal sensitivity and attachment may not be sufficient to improve cognition, and opportunities for learning need to be added. Another important question posed by the South African intervention is what is the most effective age to begin interventions? Studies of children in residential institutions provide useful information on sensitive periods. Adoption is a comprehensive intervention and Romanian children in residential institutions adopted before 6 months had no measured long-term deficits. All these topics need to be explored further and the paper by Murray et al. adds useful information. Follow-up is needed to determine if the improvement in attachment is sustained and whether any of the other benefits develop, particularly those in behaviour and mental health. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
