AB  - The purpose of this study was to examine clinicians' opinions on the appropriateness of using filial family therapy, also known as child relationship enhancement family therapy (CREFT) with adopted children and their families. Filial therapy has been very successful in treating various behavioral and emotional difficulties in children. Research indicates that adopted children can experience various difficulties, mostly related to issues with attachment. The foundation of filial therapy rests on the notion that parents are effective change agents for their children due to the natural parent-child bond that exists between them. In an adoptive family, the parent-child bond may not be formed naturally or may look different than that of a biological parent-child relationship. This study investigated whether professionals within the filial therapy field use this type of treatment with adoptive families, their reasons for this decision, common variables they consider when making this decision, and their thoughts on the appropriateness of filial therapy with this population. This study utilized a qualitative method. Ten clinicians who have conducted, researched, and/or written on the topic of filial therapy were recruited through the Association for Filial and Relationship Enhancement Methods, Inc. (AFREM). Participants were also gathered via snowball sampling. Data was collected by means of a semi-structured interview. The data from the interviews were aggregated into six themes through the use of inductive data analysis. The themes that were identified in this study were consistent with the literature on play therapy, filial therapy, and adoptive families. Ninety percent of the participants supported the use of filial therapy with adoptive families in producing positive changes within the family due to the attachment-building components of filial therapy. The majority of participants reported that their preference for using filial therapy with adoptive families is related to the need to build the attachment between the adopted child and his or her parents in order to improve problem behaviors within the parent-child relationship. This study adds a professional opinion to the filial therapy literature; a voice that is largely missing from the research. This study also supports the success of using filial therapy with adopted children, as it has been established that this is a population in need of effective treatments. Limitations of the study were addressed and recommendations were made for future research. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
