AB  - An estimated one third of American children witness domestic violence. Attachment theory predicts children exposed to domestic violence are vulnerable to experiencing problems with security of attachment to parents. When the child needs comforting and protection, the mother has become a victim and is unable to protect herself. The child is likely to experience fear with no solution. The current study examined indicators of attachment security in internal working models of preschoolers who witnessed domestic violence. Their representations were examined for qualities of attachment security, insecurity, and disorganization/disorientation, as well as, how representations relate to domestic violence. The study examined 94 preschoolers (66 clinical participants exposed to high domestic violence and 28 children from the community with less exposure). The constructs examined included: Internal representations based the MacArthur Story Stem Battery (MSSB). A report of the child's socio-emotional well-being was collected using Achenbach's Child Behavior Check List. A retrospective report profiled domestic violence using Straus's Conflicts Tactics Scale. The Parent Infant Relationship Assessment Scale (PIRGAS) assessed the mother-child relationship. The WPPSI-R was used to assess verbal ability. Univariate correlational relationships among independent variables showed: Children's parent representations include positive qualities that foster secure attachment less than half the time, making it likely that these children have insecure attachment. Characteristics of the representations of these children converge with prior empirical findings regarding the characteristics of the representations preschoolers with disoriented/disorganized attachment classifications. Paternal representations were complex and contained both positive and negative qualities. Children exposed to higher levels of domestic violence, produced fewer father representations. The maternal representations were primarily positive and appear to promote felt-security. The MSSB measures demonstrated internal validity. The MSSB showed some but limited external validity using the CBCL and PIRGAS. The limitations of self-report by a clinical sample may be contributing to invalid CBCLs. Clinicians can use this research to identify sources of distress in the parent-child relationships of preschoolers exposed to domestic violence in order to guide therapeutic interventions to provide more effective treatment. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
