AB  - Discusses the important clinical issue of working therapeutically with severely disorganized, extremely dependent parents of seriously disturbed young children. The rationale presented identifies the parental disorganization and distorted relationship with their own child as a residue of early developmental conflicts for the parent. Parenthood reactivates these unmastered issues which then hinder the parents from responding to their child in ways other than in terms of their own unmet needs. Many parents demonstrate the lack of mastery of the task of separation-individuation from their own parents. Additionally, play as a mode of mastery and exploration had not been a reward for them as children. These issues contributed to disturbance of nurturance and attachment that fostered feelings of poor self-esteem and being uncared for by others. Clinical vignettes of types of disorganizing family life patterns are presented, and the types of interventions found to be most successful are described. Findings indicate that severely disorganized families require assistance in learning new organizing and managerial roles and that practicing such roles enables parents to observe directly the positive effects on family relationships. Such observations positively reward continuing efforts to change and permit parents to feel more competent and less at the mercy of their children and life events. (16 ref) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
