AB  - The present researcher examined the relationship between foster parent acceptance and psychological adjustment with foster children's treatment attendance and adjustment. Deriving from the parenting literature and parental acceptance-rejection theory, which maintains that parenting practices influence children's social and psychological development, parental acceptance-rejection was expected to predict children's treatment attendance and behavioral and emotional adjustment. Parent psychological adjustment was hypothesized to moderate the impact of parental acceptance on treatment attendance and on child adjustment. The sample consisted of 113 foster parents who brought their foster children weekly to outpatient clinics in New York City. Foster parents completed the Parental Acceptance-Rejection Questionnaire, the Personality Assessment Questionnaire, and the Child Behavioral Checklist. Hierarchical multiple regression analysis revealed that treatment attendance was predicted by parental acceptance-rejection and that child adjustment was predicted by parental acceptance-rejection. Rejecting foster parents were significantly less likely to bring their foster children to treatment sessions than foster parents who were more accepting of their foster children. Rejecting foster parents also tended to report having foster children who were more poorly behaviorally and emotionally maladjusted than foster parents who were more accepting of their foster children. Foster parent emotional adjustment had a moderating effect on child internalizing behaviors but failed to have a moderating impact on externalizing behaviors. The findings of the present study support previous researchers who demonstrated associations between parenting style and children's social and behavioral problems. A limitation of the present study, which should be addressed by future researchers, is the restricted method of measuring parental acceptance-rejection. Future investigators may add to the literature by exploring the extent to which failures in daily parenting strategies may interact with parental acceptance-rejection to influence children's developmental outcomes. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
