AB  - The article focuses on the methodology and concepts of family treatment to the foster care situation to see whether this approach might not be more effective than the traditional individual approach. Sessions are used that include both the foster family and the foster child to help them with the many problems they face in living together. The aim is to adapt family focused treatment techniques to the purposes of foster family placement. The family-focused approach offers distinct advantages. Through the use of family sessions, all members of the foster family are involved more actively in the treatment program. Their intimate involvement increases their sense of fulfilling the foster family role, and each family member is helped to recognize the importance of his particular contribution to the success of the child's placement. The family session also gives the caseworker an opportunity to observe directly the interaction between the members of the foster family and the foster child and thus to get a more accurate picture and deeper understanding of the relationships between them. The family session has the additional advantage of minimizing the clients' concern about the worker's reactions.
