AB  - Currently in the United States, one in 10 children suffers from a mental illness that is severe enough to cause some level of impairment (National Institute of Mental Health [NIMH], 2007). One group of adolescents that is at a much higher risk for mental illness are those in foster care, as it is estimated that 40 to 85% suffer from a mental illness (Austin, 2004). Adolescents in foster care are more at risk for attachment difficulties due to their histories of trauma and displacements from their home, and may be more at risk for problem behaviors related to insecure attachment (Austin, 2004). To ensure that these adolescents get the help they need to prevent ongoing mental health issues as adults, it is important to be able to accurately assess their treatment needs and identify specific areas where they are exhibiting problem behavior. The current study utilized an existing database of adolescents ages 12 to 18 from an outpatient mental health clinic to examine changes in functioning over the course of one year in treatment. Scores on the Child and Adolescent Functional Assessment Scale (CAFAS) were used to measure treatment outcome, with lower scores indicating lower levels of impairment. For each case in the sample, three CAFAS scores were compared: the initial CAFAS score recorded at the start of treatment, the CAFAS score recorded at six months of treatment, and the CAFAS score recorded at 12 months of treatment. The sample size was 98, with approximately 50% in foster care and 50% not in foster care. Overall, results showed that both males and females not in foster care demonstrated a continued decrease in scores over the three time periods, indicating that level of impairment decreased over the course of treatment. The males in foster care also demonstrated a continued decrease in scores over the course of treatment. However, the females in foster care did not demonstrate a decrease in scores, and their CAFAS score at 12 months of treatment was the same as their initial CAFAS score, indicating no change in impairment level. Potential reasons for these findings are discussed. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
