AB  - This study examined whether or not Theraplay (Theraplay is the registered trademark of the Theraplay Institute, Wilmette, IL) increased attachment with 5 year old previously institutionalized (PI) twins. In addition, it reviewed whether or not Theraplay decreased problem behaviors in these twins. PI twins adopted from an Eastern European orphanage at the age of 3 years and 9 months underwent pretreatment and posttreatment testing which included: Achenbach's Child Behavior Checklist and Teacher Report Form, Attachment Story Completion Task (a measure of internalized representations), Marschak Interaction Method (an interactional assessment measure used with parents and child), and the Randolph Attachment Disorder Questionnaire. Additionally, Cermack's Developmental and Sensory Processing Questionnaire was used to screen for sensory processing difficulties pretreatment. The test data showed that the twins attachment increased, and their problem behaviors decreased after they received the Theraplay treatment. While Theraplay needs further study, the findings of this study suggest that Theraplay, a short term attachment based play therapy, can be an effective intervention with PI children who need to strengthen their attachment relationships. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
