AB  - This book vividly shows how creative arts and play therapy can promote children's recovery from experiences of disrupted or insecure attachment. Leading practitioners explore the impact of early relationship difficulties on children's emotions and behavior. Replete with in-depth case material, the volume brings to life a range of therapeutic approaches that utilize art, music, movement and dance, drama, creative writing, and play. Clinicians are given indispensable tools for helping children process painful emotions and memories and rebuild the capacity to form trusting attachment bonds. Introductory chapters integrate research in creative arts and play therapy with cutting-edge knowledge about attachment, trauma, and neuroscience. The value of creative expression and sensory-based experiences for treating attachment difficulties is emphasized. Part II presents a range of therapeutic approaches in rich clinical detail. Featured are ways to work with children of different ages—particularly those who are coping with multiple traumatic events or losses—as well as their caregivers. Expert contributors explain how their respective therapies address attachment issues; offer clear descriptions of their techniques and materials; and illustrate what each intervention looks like in action. Rounding out the volume. Part III discusses applications for specific populations, including complex trauma survivors, children experiencing traumatic grief, those in foster care, cross-cultural adoptees, and children displaced by homelessness or natural disasters. Providing fresh ideas that can expand the toolbox of any child clinician, this book will be read with interest by clinical psychologists; arts, play, and other creative arts therapists; child psychiatrists; social workers; and counselors, as well as graduate students. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2018 APA, all rights reserved)
