AB  - Over a half-million children are currently in the foster care system within the United States (http://www.childwelfare.gov/pubs/factsheets/foster.pdf#page=1 ). Foster children are more likely to have a trauma history due to the factors that led to their involvement with the foster care system (Pinderhughes, Jones-Harden & Guyer, 2007). A foster child's trauma exposure can be complicated and multifaceted, and often includes neglect, physical abuse, sexual abuse and/or multiple placements in the homes of caregivers. Foster parents are required to undergo training mandated by their state of residence. Though these programs provide sufficient training they often fail to address the effects of trauma and the subsequent behaviors manifested. Additionally, the state-mandated training programs are lengthy and costly for those not mandated by the state. The goal of this project was to create a free of charge, on-line training model that adds to the existing training models as well as provides additional trauma-specific information to foster parents. Furthermore, the intent was to create a training model that specifically addressed the symptom expression of physically abused children and interventions that could be utilized to ameliorate or manage these behaviors. The training model was posted on-line and was accessible to anyone with access to a computer and the Internet. The on-line training model was reviewed by a panel of 10 masters' and doctoral-level mental health clinicians. A 17-item questionnaire was provided to the reviewers, and they were asked to rate items on a 5-point Likert scale. On average, the reviewers gave positive ratings, which indicated their overall satisfaction with the on-line training model. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
