AB  - It is clear that children experiencing placement instability in foster care and during reunification face a higher likelihood of future maladjustment; however, the risks associated with placement instability are not well understood. This is especially true for young children in foster care. The current study uses a sub-sample of existing data from the Multidimensional Treatment Foster Care Preschool (MTFC-P) treatment outcome study. The sample consists of 78 pre-school age foster children randomly assigned to one of two treatment conditions: MTFC-P foster care or regular foster care (RFC). Among the variables significantly correlated with regular foster care placement instability were number of days in care, age at first foster care placement, number of incidents of maltreatment, and suspected or confirmed prenatal alcohol exposure. At study start, children having more pre-study regular foster care related placement instability were significantly more likely to display emotional and behavioral difficulties, display behavioral problems rated as more stressful by foster parents, and exhibit greater developmental delay. Children in the MTFC-P treatment condition experienced significantly fewer placement disruptions than children in the RFC treatment as usual control condition. Children with greater than average number of pre-study transitions who were placed in the MTFC-P treatment condition were more likely than their RFC counterparts to experience a successful permanent placement within 12 months. Children suspected or confirmed of prenatal drug exposure were significantly more likely to experience a successful biological parent reunification when placed in MTFC-P, than when placed in the RFC treatment as usual control condition. Findings are discussed in terms of their implications for child welfare policy, foster care interventions, and future research. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
