AB  - This study was undertaken to assess the effects of attachment therapy on the reduction of aggressive behaviors on the special needs adopted population. The study design was a prospective, pre post, quasi-experimental controlled study. The subjects were recruited through the Attachment Center at Evergreen, Colorado. Eligible subjects included children between the ages of 4 and 14 years, adopted children having lived in the present adopted home for at least one year. Parents contacted the Attachment Center between 1996 and 1997 concerned about their child's aggression and lack of attachment towards the parent, and all subjects undergoing attachment treatment returned home at the completion of treatment. Wilcoxon's signed rank tests for paired data were used to examine possible changes in aggression and delinquency in the treated subjects. Both the aggressive and delinquent items had significantly decreased for the treatment group at the time 2 measure, respectively (p = 0.02, p = 0.006). There was no significant change in the comparison group at time 2. The Wilcoxon's ranks sum test was used to compare groups on the changes in aggression and delinquency. Findings resulted in significant differences for delinquent scores over time and approaching significance for aggression scores, with the median decrease being more substantial in the treatment group (p = 0.07, aggression, p = 0.05, delinquency). Finally, relationships and correlations among all the variables were assessed. The results show that in the treated children there was a median decrease of 9.5 in the aggression scores and a median decrease of 5.0 in the delinquency scores. Also, there is evidence to show that there is a significantly larger decrease in the treatment group than in the comparison group on aggression (decrease of 9.5 in treatment group versus decrease of 4.0 in the comparison group) and on delinquency (decrease of 5.0 in the treatment group versus decrease of 1.0 in the comparison group). Aggression and delinquency scores were found to be highly, positively correlated. No significant relationships were found among the demographic variables and the changes in aggression and delinquency. Explanations for these findings are discussed along with suggestions for further research. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
