AB  - The present study seeks to discover what factors parents bring to adoption that help them to rise above the challenges of parenting an adopted child and find the experience rewarding. Participants included families (N=27) taking part in the UCLA TIES (Training, Intervention, Education, and Services) for Adoption program who had been tracked over a period of five years. The first domain of analyses examined whether children's lower levels of cognitive development act as a stressor that contributes to greater negative impact and lower levels of psychological well-being among adoptive parents. The second domain of analyses sought to determine how children's risk factors, including experiences of abuse and neglect, previous placements, age at adoption, and living with birth parents, ultimately impact adoptive parents in the years following placement. The third domain of analyses set out to explore child behavior problems among children adopted from foster care and how two moderators affect how parents react to child-related stressors. The final set of analyses focused on positive impact. Overall, the results of this study have shown that parents who are faced with greater child behavior problems experience more negative long-term outcomes. Additionally, parents of children who had lived with their birth mothers and those whose children were older at the time of placement reported more negative outcomes. Parenting stress and children's age at placement were most influential in determining parents' experience of positive impact. These findings may suggest that adoptive parents are challenged by their children's difficult behaviors and may also experience a sense of loss associated with missing the early years of their children's lives, a sentiment expressed by many parents during the interviews. Alternatively, children's early experiences prior to adoptive placement may result in insecure attachment that influences children's interactions with their adoptive parents, detracting from parents' experiences of positive impact and increasing negative impact. In light of the findings described above, interventions to aid adoptive parents facing difficult child behaviors may do well to focus strongly on preparation and education about the risks and realities of adoption from foster care. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
