AB  - This paper examines the needs of children and youth in foster care and the roles of foster parents and social workers in meeting these needs. The needs of children and youth in foster care include having deprivation replaced with nurturing, having loss replaced with gains and healthy attachments, having confusion and disorganization replaced with understanding and structure, having developmental delays ameliorated, having physical pain halted, and having emotional pain eased. Critical tasks and responsibilities of foster parents and social workers are identified, including providing child care, assessing cases and planning goals, undertaking clinical interventions, managing cases, and collaborating. The role of training in helping foster parents and social workers understand their tasks and improve their knowledge and skills is discussed in terms of historical perspectives and current issues. Components of effective training programs are identified. These components must address the issues of the role of training in meeting agency goals, the conceptual framework on which agency training is based, the design and delivery of training, and the outcomes of training. Steps that may be helpful in discussing the future direction of training are suggested. 23 references.
