AB  - Reviews the article, Effects of a foster care parent training intervention on placement changes of children in foster care by J. M. Price, P. Chamberlain, J. Landsverk, et al. (see record [rid]2008-00982-006[/rid]). This study explored the impact of a foster parent training and support intervention called KEEP on placement changes among children residing in foster care. It also examined the relationship between the number of foster care placements and whether placement changes were positive or negative. Participation in the KEEP intervention almost doubled the chances of having a positive exit and although the number of prior placements was predictive of negative exit rates among those in the control group, it was not a significant predictor among participants who received the intervention. The authors indicate that the KEEP intervention mitigated the negative impact of multiple prior placements. They suggest that placement instability is an important risk factor and should be minimized for children in foster care. They also support the implementation of parent training interventions focused on behavior management and helping foster parents increase their knowledge and skills in coping with behavior problems to reduce the likelihood of changes in placement among children in the foster care system. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
