AB  - With the divorce rate at about 50%, one million children will experience their parents' divorce each year in the United States. Despite the fact that almost 90% of noncustodial parents are fathers, there is very little professional literature available to help fathers figure cut how to be effective noncustodial parents. This dissertation project consisted of developing, facilitating, and qualitatively evaluating a group intervention for noncustodial fathers. The group was focused on improving noncustodial fathers' relationships with their children in an effort to keep fathers involved in their children's lives and minimize the negative effects of divorce or separation. The group curriculum was created based on concepts from attachment theory. The intervention was designed to be a combination of a process and psychoeducational group, and was also intended to serve as a source of support. An eight week group intervention called The Staying Connected Group for Fathers was implemented at Xanthos, Alameda Family Services. Four noncustodial fathers participated in the project. Results from the pre- and post-group questionnaires, as well as the author's process notes, reveal that the participants clearly found the group to be a helpful, supportive, learning experience. Each of the group members experienced a strong sense of support from attending the group and gained knowledge of behaviors, skills, and/or ways of interacting with their children that promote good quality father-child relationships. Results from this project suggest that attachment theory is an efficient theoretical model from which to base an intervention that is focused on noncustodial fathers and their children. Clinical implications include the need for increased efforts to reach out to noncustodial fathers. Furthermore, crucial areas of intervention identified include addressing the overwhelming experience of helplessness, due to lack of influence over their children's lives and feeling powerless within the legal system, and the issue of gender role expectations, specifically, the effects that male role socialization has on developing an identity as a father who is able to foster a good quality father-child relationship. Additional considerations for future interventions are explored. Further studies that include control groups and longitudinal follow ups are merited to demonstrate effectiveness with more certainty. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
