AB  - In view of the fact that one of the critical predictors for adult mental health problems is childhood disorder, the issue of applying effective intervention in childhood and adolescence becomes crucial. Cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) offers a promising approach to addressing needs for treatment efficacy, on the condition that social workers adapt basic CBT to the specific needs of children and design the intervention holistically to foster change in children. This chapter suggests a route for applying effective interventions in the day-to-day work of social workers who are primarily involved in direct interventions with children and adolescents and their families. Topics include: main goals of child intervention, the basics of CBT with adults, adaptation of CBT basics to children, a new model for applying CBT with children: skills-directed therapy (SDT), the importance of integrating developmental components in CBT with children (age, gender, and cognitive stage as mediators in child therapy; information processing as a significant component in CBT with children; language skills as crucial components in child therapy; emotional and social components as crucial skills in child therapy; the role of family environment), the SDT model for children (1. cognitive restructuring, 2. problem analysis, 3. attentional focus, 4. self-control practice), and SDT application to children with aggressive behavior. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)
