AB  - Explores several issues pertaining to children with emotional or behavioral problems in foster or residential homes, the characteristics and needs of the children, and the attempts of social agencies and treatment centers to deal with their problems. Several parameters of treatment in residential settings are defined. It is asserted that residential treatment facilities play a significant role in the treatment and disposition of children in out-of-home placements. The importance of the social milieu in influencing the child's behavior in such settings is emphasized, including the impact of direct care staff who are the true treatment agents. Therapeutic approaches need to address such issues as attachment and loss, damaged self-esteem and hopelessness, trauma and abuse, lack of social skills, and the teaching of basic values. Minimal criteria for defining treatment are outlined. It is concluded that there is a need for process and outcome research to determine what is therapeutic in residential treatment settings. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
