AB  - The most frequent problems demonstrated by long term foster children were lack of concentration, temper tantrums, stealing and attention-demanding behaviour and these frequently persisted into adolescence. New parents may need help in developing consistent and effective control over such behaviour and support for properly exercised parental authority should be forthcoming from the placing agency. Parents may also need help of a different kind to develop strategies for achieving more sustained attention in their foster children. Effective parenting is more likely to result worn modifying parenting style in accord with the particular needs and characteristics of the child concerned. Advice may be given about strategies for dealing with difficulties, but this needs to be compatible with the new parents style and the likely response of the child.
