AB  - Families eligible for the study were those with a child placed from care for adoption between 3 and 18 months previously. All the children were between ages 3 and 7 years 11 months at placement, were not suffering from severe physical or learning disabilities and had not been placed with relatives or their current foster parent. An initial estimation was that 100 adoptive families could be recruited from about 12 English local authority permanent placement units. A screening questionnaire, Strengths & Difficulties Questionnaire, was used to select into the study only those children with serious psycho-social difficulties for whom the intensive intervention could be justified. Two SDQs were to be completed by the social worker with recent knowledge of the child and by the child’s adoptive parents. Screening questionnaires were completed for 178 children, and the parents of 80 were eligible for inclusion by virtue of having at least one child in the family with a high SDQ score; 38 adoptive parents agreed to participate in the trial. We were pleased to report that none of the adoptive placements disrupted while families were involved in the trial. The prediction that the children's psycho-social scores would improve after the parent advice sessions did not hold as little change was evident. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
