AB  - Discusses international adoption, specifically the adoption of Romanian children, and the role of developmental research in this process. Research on adoption usually involves a 'natural' design, which allows for examination of the effects of interventions which cannot be carried out ethically using true experimental designs. Such studies may address the issues of 'plasticity' and 'critical periods' in development, and examine the importance of specific relationships and types of stimulation during particular periods in early childhood. Research on international adoption also has implications for social policy, by indicating the need for specialized informational and support services before, during, and post-adoption. Adoption and immigration policies may be directly influenced by the results of research on outcomes for international adoptees. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)
