AB  - Review 3 basic issues that are important in the assessment and treatment of preschool-age children: temperament, issues in attachment and separation-individuation, and impulse control. Although these 3 issues are not unique to the preschool-age child, the appear to take on particular importance in this age group, and problems in these areas frequently result in requests for psychiatric consultation. Topics discussed include: classification of temperament (easy, difficult, slow-to-warm-up), goodness of fit, temperament and school functioning, temperament and attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder, significance of difficult temperament, development of attachment, why infants become attached, separation anxiety, secure and insecure attachment, influences on attachment (maternal and infant characteristics), applications of attachment theory to preschool-age children (foster care), development of impulse control, problem-solving styles, control of emotions, delaying gratification, and the parents' role in children's impulsiveness. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)
