AB  - This first issue of the journal 'Attachment and Human Development' begins with an evocative report on long-term family foster care. One of the papers presents a compelling model of parenting with five dimensions, largely based on attachment theory. The paper describes the model in detail, with narrative examples, illustrating how it is being used as a guide to support and promote effective foster care for highly vulnerable children in the school-aged and early adolescent years. In another article the authors write about a vulnerable mother who lost custody of her infant to foster care, before undertaking much hard and valuable therapeutic work that permitted her to regain and retain custody of her child. Another paper presents fascinating results concerning the intergenerational transmission of role-reversal in a non-clinical sample of 138 children, mothers, and fathers. The opportunity presented by the last paper is for researchers to classify parental behavior in a way that is likely to cohere with child-parent behavior. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
