AB  - This study examined relationships between parenting attitudes and behavior and parent-child interaction in 46 mother-child dyads receiving services from one of two infant development programs. Mothers completed questionnaires assessing parenting stress, sense of parenting competence and behavior, knowledge of infant development, perceived social support, and were videotaped in a parent-child freeplay session. In addition, mothers were interviewed about their reasons for participating in and satisfaction with the intervention services they received. Mothers and children were seen twice approximately four months apart. Mothers selected center- and parent support-based services so that their children could interact with other children and to foster children's development. Mothers selected home-based services for convenience, comfort, and for child safety and health. Mothers chose a combination of services so that the child could receive individualized attention in the home setting, and their children could receive social interaction available in the center setting. Mothers were overwhelmingly satisfied with the services. Positive aspects of the services included children's developmental progress, the information they received and support and understanding obtained from other parents. Mothers' reported greater satisfaction in the parenting role and exhibited more sensitivity toward their children, and children appeared more sensitive, less compulsive compliant, and less difficult with their mothers at the final assessment. Higher levels of parenting stress were correlated with lower reported parenting competence, and less sensitive and more controlling behavior during the parent-child interaction. Perceived social support was negatively correlated with parenting stress. With the exception that older maternal age was associated with less sensitive behavior toward children, and more difficulty in specific aspects of parenting, the findings support previous literature. These findings also suggest that among predominantly middle-income, suburban mother-child dyads participating in infant programs, older maternal age may be associated with greater infant impairment and other factors that may result in more difficulty in the parenting role. Findings supported the importance of early intervention services that address both maternal and child needs, as well as the interrelatedness between parent and child functioning for families with a child diagnosed with a developmental disability. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
