AB  - By stepping into a child's life and providing nurturance and supervision, foster parents serve an important role in our society. More and more, children who are placed within this system have been abused, exposed to drugs, and endured traumas, and, therefore, are dealing with psychological disorders that increase problematic behaviors (Dorsey et al., 2008). The individuals who provide care for children or adolescents who present with more severe behavioral problems, mental health diagnoses, or more demanding needs are considered therapeutic foster parents (TFP). Despite the increased need for trainings specific to these more advanced needs, current trainings used nationally do not sufficiently address salient topics. In response to the lack of advanced trainings for TFP, the researcher developed an advanced training curriculum—SMARTIE. This study is a quasi-experimental, time-series design that evaluates the effects of this training on TFP in southeastern Virginia. It was hypothesized that there would be a decrease in reported stress and an increase in skill level as a result of participating in the advanced training. Skill level was conceptualized in this study as a combination of parents' feelings of competence and level of disruptive behaviors reported. It was also hypothesized that spiritual well-being would be negatively correlated with reported stress levels. Forty parents of children/adolescents from two local offices completed the assessments and attended training sessions. Parenting Stress Index (PSI), Stress Index for Parents of Adolescents (SIPA), Parenting Sense of Competence Scale (PSOC), and Disruptive Behavior Disorder Rating Scale (DBDRS) were completed as a pre- and posttest measure of any significant changes. Participants also completed the Spiritual Well-Being Scale at the first data collection. Results showed that there was a statistically significant decrease in reported stress levels. There was no difference in number of disruptive behaviors or the parents' feelings of competency. The results also indicated there was a significant negative relationship between spiritual well-being and stress. Additionally, the results indicated a significant positive relationship between various domains of stress. Implications for the child welfare field, limitations, and directions for future studies are discussed. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
