AB  - Since a review of studies concerning the effects of out-of-home care (OOHC) on individual differences in attachment quality for children suggests that the data are irrelevant to issues derived from the ethological-organizational perspective, alternative approaches are illustrated in 2 studies. In Study 1, 10 boys (aged 2 yrs 3 mo to 2 yrs 10 mo) entering a high-quality part-time nursery school program were used to establish the feasibility of a within-Ss, home-observational design (Q-sort descriptions by 2 observers). Findings indicate that the nursery school experience was associated with immediate changes in Ss' behavior at home but that these effects were minor and transient. In Study 2, data were used from a study by the lst author and colleagues (see record [rid]1981-07880-001[/rid]) on the relationship between OOHC and the quality of infant–mother attachment in an economically disadvantaged population. 90 mothers and their 24-mo-old children were studied for effects of mother's early return to work (child placed in OOHC prior to 12 mo of age), late return to work (child placed in OOHC between 12 and 18 mo of age), and no work (child received in-home care through the 1st 18 mo of life). Knowledge of infant–parent attachment histories was used to interpret and explain daycare effects. Findings suggest that the expected sequelae of attachment may by disrupted for OOHC children when such care starts prior to the 1st birthday. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
