AB  - In this study, I evaluated the efficacy of a parenting program (TAKE-5) provided by a local nonprofit organization to foster parents of sexually abused children. Participants consisted of 30 foster parents, predominately married, Caucasian, females, who cared for children ages 3 to 17. Administered measures included: Eyberg Child Behavior Inventory (Eyberg & Pincus, 1999), Parental Emotional Reaction Questionnaire (Cohen & Mannarino, 1996), Parenting Sense of Competence Scale (Johnston & Mash, 1989), and the Parenting Stress Index- Short Form (Abidin, 1995). Measures were administered at three time points: before, after, and follow-up. A randomized controlled trial was designed to evaluate the intervention, including treatment and wait-list control groups, and was evaluated with a series of mixed design ANOVAs. The level of significance was adjusted to p = .10 in order to control for Type II error and pairwise comparisons were conducted as follow-up tests. Significant timegroup interaction effects were indicated for parent report of child behavior problems, Wilks' Λ; = .84, F(2, 27) = 2.50, p = .10, partial² = .16, parent emotional reactions, Wilks' Λ; = .82, F(2, 27) = 2.97, p = .07, partial² = .18, and parenting self-efficacy, Wilks' Λ; = .82, F(2, 27) = 2.91, p = .07, partial² = .18. Pairwise comparisons indicated a statistically significant increase in parenting self-efficacy and decrease in parental emotional distress for the treatment group over the course of the intervention, these findings remained stable at the follow-up assessment. Although statistical significance was not met for the remaining hypotheses, a change in the expected direction was observed for every outcome measure and supported with small to large effect sizes. Findings imply that participation in the TAKE-5 program results in long lasting positive parenting outcomes that are associated with healthier child functioning. An unexpected finding was that the wait-list control participants indicated increases in reported child behavior problems, parenting stress, and distress to sexual abuse while waiting for treatment, implying that treatment is most beneficial when made readily available. This evaluation provides some of the empirical evidence needed for the TAKE-5 program to be established as evidence based. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
