AB  - This study was an exploratory investigation of the adoptive parent training needs relative to the adoption of an older child, specifically in the areas of attachment and behavior management. As adoption laws change, more and more older children are being adopted. It is precisely these adoptions that have such a high risk of disruption and dissolution. Two areas in particular are shown to be positively correlated with adoption disruption and/or dissolution: attachment and behavior management. The data was collected by a survey questionnaire, authored by the researcher. The main body of the survey consists of two parts: attachment and behavior management. Each part consists of three subsections: most commonly occurring experiences between the adoptive parent and the older adoptive child; level of adoptive parent skills/abilities in relation to the older adoptive child, and topics of interest to the older child adoptive parent. Interviews were also conducted to gain a greater depth and subtlety of information. The survey results indicate that although adoptive parents feel confident and able in both attachment and behavior areas, their awareness of attachment issues and skills to deal with problems of attachment are either undeveloped or underdeveloped. A lack of understanding of basic attachment processes and a denial of the child's pre-adoptive experiences as relevant to the attachment process was revealed. Based upon the findings from this research, a model training program should include education about attachment theory, stages of attachment, and concrete strategies for dealing with behaviors related to attachment problems. The data also revealed that experiences related to communication and behavior management were common, especially early in the adoptive process, with those issues seemingly better understood. Here was expressed the respondents greatest areas of interest as it related to receiving information or talking to a professional, and a model training should include those aspects of training that command adopters' interest. Avenues for further research include administration of the survey to different populations for comparative purposes, further qualitative studies, and longitudinal studies to see changes in the data over time. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
