AB  - This study focuses on an intervention applied to a parent/child attunement process. The intervention has been designed to support and guide first time adoptive parents as they establish a solid and effective relationship with their new child. Recognizing that their course of adjustment is both similar to and different from biological parents, an intervention instrument to fortify and empower the mutual process of the parents and infant getting to know each other was designed. This intervention, the Adoption FANA (Family Administered Neonatal Activities), was adapted from the original FANA (Cardone & Gilkerson, 1989, 1990, 1992). The adaptation was applied to one adoptive family: a case study approach was used to develop in-depth information about how and how well the intervention design works. The data were collected through videotaping interactions between the baby and her parents, as well as through interviews with the parents. The videotaped interactions focused on three themes: (1) The quality of synchrony between the parents and infant: face to face interactions, eye contact, gaze aversion, and parent response to crying; (2) Self-regulation: how often the baby attempts to self regulate by sucking on her hand, touching her feet together, changing states of consciousness or gaze aversion, and do the parents respect the baby's cues? (3) Consolability techniques used by the parents with their infant. A fourth theme, parents' expression of adoption related issues, was another focus during the course of the study. The videotaping and interviewing began when the infant was two weeks old and culminated when she was three months old. The case study family stated that having the opportunity to expound upon their feelings and thoughts about their adoption journey, coupled with the experience of learning about their infant's behaviors and competencies, enhanced their ability to become attuned with their new infant. Research findings confirm that they did become more successfully attuned to their infant.
