AB  - The effectiveness of foster parent training has been debated in the literature. One position is that it may be part of the solution to repeated placements in foster care; the other view holds that training foster parents is not warranted due to its limited effectiveness. The purpose of this study was to evaluate the outcome of training foster parents with the Love-and-Logic parent training course, a highly endorsed intervention. Foster parents assigned to one of three study groups (the seven-week Love-and-Logic course, a group that read the Love-and-Logic parent book, and a control group that received no training) were evaluated before and after the training, as well as a follow-up measure a few months later. Data was collected with the Parent-Child Relationship Inventory, a measure of parenting skills and attitudes, for pre-training, post-training, and follow-up data. This study underscores the need for effective foster parenting to provide the most stable alternative care for youth in the child welfare system. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
