AB  - Many youth aging out of foster care experience material hardship such as poor housing, homelessness, and food insufficiency. This study examined the transition to young adulthood of youth aging out of foster care, focusing on their experience of material hardship. In particular, the study examined perceived and received social support as critical factors that explained varying levels of material hardship among youth aging out of foster care. The study focused on youths' relationships with birth parents and out-of-home caregivers and examined how intimacy and kin relationships of these social ties were associated with perceived and received social support. Ordinary least squares (OLS) and probit regression analyses were conducted, using the data originally collected for evaluating effects of the Life Skills Training program as a part of the Chafee Independent Living Program Evaluation (U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, n.d.). The dissertation study targeted youths who were in foster care at the age of 17 and left care before the age of 20 and assessed their intimacy with birth parents and out-of-home caregivers, kinship ties with out-of-home caregivers, perceived and received social support, and material hardship. The study found significant correlation between social support and material hardship of youths aging out of foster care. Lower levels of perceived social support while in care and their decline after leaving care significantly raised the likelihood of experiencing material hardship. In addition, intimacy and kinship ties were found to be significant factors influencing support provision. Intimate relationships with out-of-home caregivers were positively related to youths' perception of available social support. However, such relationships did not prevent youths from experiencing a support decline. Kinship ties between youths and out-of-home caregivers are a factor that prevent youths from experiencing a support decline after leaving care. Findings from this study suggest that departure from care can weaken supportive social ties formed within the system and thereby adversely influence economic conditions of youth. Therefore, it is recommended that child welfare policy and practice should make efforts to help youth establish long-lasting ties within the system and support those relationships after leaving care. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
